A cylinder of mass $m$ and radius $r$ initially rests on two supports of the same height, initially placed next to each other. One support is stationary, while the other slides from under the cylinder at a constant velocity $v$. Determine the normal force $N$ exerted by the stationary support on the cylinder when the points of contact between the cylinder and the supports are a distance $r\sqrt2$ apart. <em>Note: The original problem statement supplied a hint that was incorrect and overparameterized the system.</em>
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.15]{ballsupport}
    \end{center}

solution:
Notice that as the support moves, the axis of the cylinder moves along a circle of radius $r$ about the point of contact $A$ with the stationary support. Thus, at the given moment the velocity $u$ of the axis moves perpendicularly to the radius drawn to $A$. Since the axis moves in a circle, we have centripetal acceleration in the direction along the radius:
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{ballreal}
    \end{center}
    Notice the normal force from the other support is perpendicular to the other forces, so it contributes no net force. Then, balancing forces yields $$m\frac{u^2}{r}=\frac{mg}{\sqrt2}-N$$Since the axis of the cylinder is always halfway between the two supports, it should move at a horizontal velocity $v/2$. This means that $u/\sqrt2=v/2$, so $u=v/\sqrt2$. Combining these equations, $$N=\frac{mg}{\sqrt2}-m\frac{u^2}{r}=\boxed{\frac{mg}{\sqrt2}-m\frac{v^2}{2r}}$$

problem:
Find the location of the center of mass (the point at which a centripetal or gravitational force can be assumed to act on) of a uniform semicircular arc of radius $R$.
\begin{center}
        \includegraphics[width=0.2\textwidth]{arc}
    \end{center}

solution:
Imagine appending another semicircular arc to make this arc a complete circle. If this arc were to spin at an angular velocity $\omega$, then we know from solution 6b that the tension in the arc is $T=\mu\omega^2R^2,$ where $\mu$ is the mass per unit length. Then, analyzing forces on solely the semicircle: \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.15]{arc2}
    \end{center}If the distance from the center of mass to the center of the circle is $d$, we can see that $$2T=m\omega^2d=\mu\pi R\omega^2d\Rightarrow d=\boxed{\frac{2}{\pi}R}$$

problem:
Two balls are placed on a weightless support formed by two smooth inclined planes that both form an angle $\theta$ with the horizontal. The support can slide without friction along a horizontal plane. The upper ball of mass $m_1$ is released. Determine the condition under which the lower ball of mass $m_2$ starts moving up the support at this moment.
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=0.25\textwidth]{climb}
\end{center}

solution:
Since the support is weightless, the net force on it must be 0. This means the mass $m_2$ must rise up the left inclined plane, as to keep the net horizontal force on the support (generated by the normal force between the support and the masses) equal to 0. However, the support may in fact accelerate (the $F=ma$ equation is still valid if $0=0a$ but $a\neq 0$). Let's assume the support accelerates to the right at $a$. Then, shifting into the rest frame of the support, each mass gains a weight $ma$ towards the left. \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.18]{support}
    \end{center}Notice the normal forces $N$ have to be equal in magnitude to maintain 0 net force on the support. Balancing forces on the balls perpendicular to each plane, \begin{gather*}
        N=m_2g\cos\theta+m_2a\sin\theta\\
        N=m_1g\cos\theta-m_1a\sin\theta
    \end{gather*}The condition that $m_2$ starts rolling upward is that $m_2a\cos\theta > m_2g\sin\theta$. Notice we can solve for $a$ using the two force equations from earlier, where $a=(m_1-m_2)g\cot\theta/(m_1+m_2).$ Then, the condition we need can be found as $$\frac{m_1-m_2}{m_1+m_2}>\tan^2\theta$$Or alternatively, using trig identities, $$\boxed{m_2<m_1\cos2\theta}$$

