A person hoists one of two loads of equal mass at a constant velocity $v$. Initially, the upper pulley is prevented from rotating by some force. At the moment when the two loads are at the same height $h$, the upper pulley is released. What load hits the floor first, and at what time $t$ does this happen? Assume that the person continues to pull the rope at the same constant velocity $v$. The pulleys and ropes are massless. 
    \begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=0.22\textwidth]{person}
\end{center}

solution:
The condition of the person pulling on the rope allows the rope to be in tension the entire time. Otherwise, the system is equivalent to having the free end of the rope fixed. Using this, let the tension in the lower string be $T$. Then, the force equations are \begin{gather*}ma_1=mg-T\\
    ma_2=mg-2T\end{gather*}
    And the equation of constraint is $a_1=-a_2$. Solving the system, $a_1=2g/5$, which means the left block accelerates downward and hits the ground first. Since the block initially moves up at speed $v$, we can use the kinematic equation $$h=-vt+\frac12\frac{2g}{5}t^2$$which has the solution $$t=\boxed{\frac{5v}{2g}+\sqrt{\left(\frac{5v}{2g}\right)^2+\frac{5h}{g}}}$$
